Getting and Cleaning Data - Peer-Graded Course Project for Module 4 -
README
================
Author: sagiff

# Project Description

The purpose of this project is to demonstrate your ability to collect,
work with, and clean a data set. The goal is to prepare tidy data that
can be used for later analysis.

Results of this assignment should include: 1) a tidy data set as
described below, 2) a link to a Github repository with the script for
performing the analysis, 3) a code book that describes the variables,
the data, and any transformations or work that were performed to clean
up the data called CodeBook.md, and 4) a README.md in the repo with the
scripts. This repo explains how all of the scripts work and how they are
connected.

##Data Source:
The data used for this project can be found here:
https://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/getdata%2Fprojectfiles%2FUCI%20HAR%20Dataset.zip

## Code Description:

This script (run_analysis.R) will take smartphone, labeling, and
variable name data from several .txt files and combine them. Data
transformations will ensure variable names and data format are
consistent, and only include data that is requested per the assignment.
All data will be combined and properly filtered in one data set. A
second data set will summarize the data by subjectid and activitylabel
and will include averages of all measurements.

1.  Load the dplyr library.

``` r
library(dplyr)
```

2.  Set the working directory to the folder that contains the data
    files.

``` r
setwd("C:/Users/m182531/Documents/UCI HAR Dataset")
```

3.  Check to make sure the necessary files exist in the directory. If
    the file does not exist, a message will pop up indicating that the
    file does not exist, and `stop()` will prevent further lines of code
    from being executed.

``` r
  if(!file.exists("features.txt")) {
    stop(paste("File does not exist:", "features.txt"))
  }
  if(!file.exists("subject_test.txt")) {
    stop(paste("File does not exist:", "subject_test.txt"))
  }
  if(!file.exists("X_test.txt")) {
    stop(paste("File does not exist:", "X_test.txt"))
  }
  if(!file.exists("y_test.txt")) {
    stop(paste("File does not exist:", "y_test.txt"))
  }
  if(!file.exists("subject_train.txt")) {
    stop(paste("File does not exist:", "subject_train.txt"))
  }
  if(!file.exists("X_train.txt")) {
    stop(paste("File does not exist:", "X_train.txt"))
  }
  if(!file.exists("y_train.txt")) {
    stop(paste("File does not exist:", "y_train.txt"))
  }
```

4.  Read/load the file features.txt into R (which contains the variable
    names for the data) as a data frame using `read.table()` and store
    as a variable `features`. Transpose the rows into columns using
    `t()` so it can later be combined with the data as the column names.
    Remove additional white spaces (`strip.white`) from the variable
    names.

``` r
features <- read.table("features.txt", sep="", header=FALSE, strip.white=TRUE, stringsAsFactors=FALSE)
features <- as.data.frame(t(features[2]))
```

5.  Check the dimensions of `features` using `dim()` to ensure it has 1
    row and 561 columns.

``` r
dim(features)
```

    ## [1]   1 561

6.  Clean up the variable names in `features` using `tolower()` and
    `gsub()`: change all letters to lowercase, remove parentheses,
    change “-” and “,” to “.”. `gsub("\.{2}", ".", .)` removes any
    excess periods.

``` r
features <- features %>% tolower() %>% gsub("\\(","", .) %>% gsub("\\)", "", .) %>% gsub("-", "\\.", .) %>% gsub(",", "\\.", .) %>% gsub("\\.{2,}", ".", .)
```

7.  Read/load the other files into R as data frames using
    `read.table()`. Define column names (`col.names`) and remove
    additional white spaces (`strip.white`).

``` r
subject_test <- read.table("subject_test.txt", sep="", col.names="subjectid", strip.white=TRUE, stringsAsFactors=FALSE) ##Contains study ids for the test group
X_test <- read.table("X_test.txt", sep="", col.names=features, strip.white=TRUE, stringsAsFactors=FALSE) ##Contains the activity data for the test group
y_test <- read.table("y_test.txt", sep="", col.names="activitylabel", strip.white=TRUE, stringsAsFactors=FALSE) ##Contains the activity labels for the test group
subject_train <- read.table("subject_train.txt", sep="", col.names="subjectid", strip.white=TRUE, stringsAsFactors=FALSE) ##Contains study ids for the train group
X_train <- read.table("X_train.txt", sep="", col.names=features, strip.white=TRUE, stringsAsFactors=FALSE) ##Contains the activity data for the train group
y_train <- read.table("y_train.txt", sep="", col.names="activitylabel", strip.white=TRUE, stringsAsFactors=FALSE) ##Contains the activity labels for the train group
```

8.  Check the dimensions of each data frame using `dim()`.All of the
    `_test` files should contain the same number of rows. `subject_test`
    and `y_test` should have 1 column. `X_test` should have 561 columns.
    All of the `_train` files should contain the same number of rows.
    `subject_train` and `y_train` should have 1 column. `X_train` should
    have 561 columns.

``` r
dim(subject_test)
```

9.  Create a list of activity labels using `c()`. Convert the activity
    labels contained in `y_test` and `y_train` from numbers (1, 2, 3, 4,
    5, 6) to characters(1=walking, 2=walkingupstairs,
    3=walkingdownstairs, 4=sitting, 5=standing, 6=laying).

``` r
activity_labels <- c("walking", "walkingupstairs", "walkingdownstairs", "sitting", "standing", "laying")
y_test$activitylabel <- activity_labels[y_test$activitylabel]
y_train$activitylabel <- activity_labels[y_train$activitylabel]
```

10. Combine the 3 `_test` files together into one data frame by columns
    using `cbind()`. Combine the 3 `_train` files together into one data
    frame by columns using `cbind()`.

``` r
test_data <- cbind(subject_test, y_test, X_test)
train_data <- cbind(subject_train, y_train, X_train)
```

11. Check the dimensions of `test_data` and `train_data` using `dim()`.
    Their dimensions should be 2947x563 and 7352x563 respectively. They
    should both have the same number of columns. The number of rows
    should remain the same as before.

``` r
dim(test_data)
```

    ## [1] 2947  563

``` r
dim(train_data)
```

    ## [1] 7352  563

12. Combine all data from the `test_data` and `train_data` together into
    one data frame called `merged_data` by rows using `rbind()`. Sort
    the data by `subjectid`, then by `activitylabel` using `order()`.

``` r
merged_data <- rbind(test_data, train_data)
merged_data[order(merged_data$subjectid, merged_data$activitylabel), ]
```

13. Check the dimensions of `merged_data`. The number of rows should be
    the sum of rows of `test_data` and `train_data` (2947+7352=10,299).
    The number of columns should remain the same (563).

``` r
dim(merged_data)
```

    ## [1] 10299   563

14. From `merged_data`, retain the first two columns (`subjectid` and
    `activitylabel`) and from the rest of the columns (variables),
    select only the measurements on mean or standard deviation for each
    measurement using `select()` and matching column/variable names
    containing “mean” or “std” (not case sensitive).

``` r
merged_data <- merged_data %>% select(1:2, matches("[Mm][Ee][Aa][Nn]") | matches("[Ss][Tt][Dd]"))
```

15. Save `merged_data` to a txt file using `write.table()`.

``` r
write.table(merged_data, file="merged_data.txt", row.names=FALSE)
```

16. Create a second independent data set with the average of each
    variable for each activity (`activitylabel`) and each subject
    (`subjectid`) using `group_by()` to group the data by `subjectid`
    and `activitylabel`, and then use `summarize()` to calculate the
    average of all other columns. Columns containing these averages will
    start with “`avg`” followed by the original column name.

``` r
summary_data <- merged_data %>% group_by(subjectid, activitylabel) %>% summarize(across(everything(), \(x) mean(x, na.rm=TRUE), .names="avg.{col}"))
```

    ## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'subjectid'. You can override using the
    ## `.groups` argument.

17. Save `summary_data` to a txt file using `write.table()`.

``` r
write.txt(summary_data, file="summary_data.txt", row.names=FALSE)
```
